        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "Seems like it needs to be\r\n\r\n```\r\n\t\tbool got_slash = !strchr (\"/\\\\\", text[j+1];   /* true if next char is one of these slashes */\r\n\t\tif (text[j] == ':' && text[j+1] && (!got_shash || (got_slash && !(isupper (text[j-1]) || islower (text[j-1])))) colon = j;\r\n```\r\n\r\nThen, got_slash = false and we set the colon. If we do find a slash then we check if the previous is a letter.  if both a slash and a previous letter then we have \"C:\\\" and exclude it.\r\n\r\nIt may be that we only need to look for the slash.  However, I am trying to worry about a potential case where a UNIX hard path follows a colon, e.g. -SqN4:/my/path, even though I do not think we ever give a filename directly after this separator, but if we ever needed to then it would at least catch that particular case (because 4 is not a letter).\r\n\r\nDoes this looks OK to you, @seisman ?",
